<DIV4 N="5" TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&sect; V.</HEAD>
<P>On account of the great &s;carcity of &s;ilver coin, occa&s;ioned by the expor|tation of $$$ver and the imp$$tation of gold, a motion was made to put a &s;top to the growing $span$ the value of gold &s;pecies. The commons examined a $span$ had been made to the trea&s;ury by Sir I&s;aac $span$ on this &s;ubject. Mr. Ca&s;wel explained the na|ture $word$ a $span$ carried on by the Dutch and Hamburghers, in con|cert $span$ of England and other traders, for exporting the &s;ilver coin and $span$ being $word$ at the mint, yielded a profit of fifteen pence upon $word$ $word$ The hou&s;e, in an addre&s;s to the king, de&s;ired that a proclamation might be i&s;&s;ued, forbidding all per&s;ons to utter or receive guineas at a higher rate than one and twenty &s;hillings each. His maje&s;ty complied
