e lands in Scotland. &sect; <HI>XXVIII.</HI> Takes po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion of Edinburgh. &sect; <HI>XXIX.</HI> Defeats Sir John Cope at Pre&s;ton-pans. &sect; <HI>XXX.</HI> Ef|forts of the friends of the government in Scotland. &sect; <HI>XXXI.</HI> Precautions taken in England. &sect; <HI>XXXII.</HI> The prince-pretender reduces Carli&s;le, and penetrates as far as Derby. Con&s;ternation of the Londoners. &sect; <HI>XXXIII.</HI> The rebels retreat into Scotland. &sect; <HI>XXXIV.</HI> They inve&s;t the ca&s;tle of Stirling. &sect; <HI>XXXV.</HI> The king's troops under Hawley are wor&s;ted at Falkirk. &sect; <HI>XXXVI.</HI> The duke of Cumberland a&s;&s;umes the command of the &s;orces in Scotland. &sect; <HI>XXXVII.</HI> The relels undertake the &s;iege of Fort William.</P>
